article.description: Jalen Rose had 30 points and Donyell Marshall had 18 points and 18 rebounds as the Chicago Bulls defeated the Milwaukee Bucks 97-95.
article.headline: Rose, Marshall propel Bulls past Bucks
article.linkText: Rose (30 points) nearly unstoppable as Bulls edge Bucks
article.story:
CHICAGO (AP) -- Jalen Rose sometimes feels as though he can't be stopped, which might have been the case Saturday night.
Rose

Rose had 30 points and Donyell Marshall had 18 points and 18 rebounds as the Chicago Bulls defeated the Milwaukee Bucks 97-95. Sam Cassell tied the game at 95 on a baseline jumper with 32.3 left, but Rose responded by hitting a fadeaway jumper with 8.1 seconds remaining. Tim Thomas was guarding Rose at the time. "As a competitor you feel you can take anybody, sometimes there is no 'D' for great offense," Rose said. Jay Williams stole Ray Allen's pass with 0.5 seconds left and was fouled. He missed both free throws, but the Bucks could not get off a final shot. "Jalen hit a big shot and Ray fumbled it and that was it,'' George Karl said. "He (Allen) was ready to take it inside with the shooters on the weak side.'' Chicago has won three of its last four games since losing nine straight, while the Bucks have lost five of their last seven. "We are definitely playing a lot better then we were a couple of weeks ago,'' Marshall said. "We can't be content with this.'' Milwaukee never led in the second half and trailed most of the game. "We should've came out of the gate more aggressively, then we wouldn't have been down so quickly,'' Thomas said. Sam Cassell and Allen each finished with 29. Cassell scored 20 in the second half and Allen had 17. Cassell cut into the Bulls' lead by scoring seven consecutive points for the Bucks to key a 10-2 run. Thomas hit a jumper to get the Bucks within two with 7:22 left in the game, but Rose and Williams responded by hitting consecutive 3-pointers for the Bulls to give them a 88-80 lead with 5:47 left. Cassell hit a 3-pointer and a jumper to make it 89-87 with 4:03 left. Williams converted a three-point play at the end of the first quarter which started a 10-0 Bulls run. Marcus Fizer scored five points during the span and hit a free throw to give the Bulls a 29-25 lead with 9:11 left in the second quarter. Williams had 16 points for the Bulls. Marshall hit a 3-pointer to extend the Bulls' lead to 10 in the second half, but Allen hit a half-court shot at the buzzer to cut the Bulls lead to 50-43.

Game notes
Jamal Crawford played 18 minutes after returning from his grandmother's funeral in Seattle. ... Eddie Robinson missed his third consecutive game with a bruised knee. ... The Bucks have not won consecutive games in over a month. ... Cassell was 14-for-16 from the foul line.
